Here is the completed code:

```matlab
function [intg, best] = myIntegral(range,N,f)
    x = linspace(range(1), range(2), N+1);
    dx = (range(2) - range(1))/N;
    Ileft = 0;
    Iright = 0;
    Itrap = 0;
    for i = 1:N
        Ileft = Ileft + f(x(i))*dx;
        Iright = Iright + f(x(i+1))*dx;
        Itrap = Itrap + 0.5*(f(x(i))+f(x(i+1)))*dx;
    end
    Itrue = integral(f, range(1), range(2));
    intg = [{'Left Riemann'}, {'Right Riemann'}, {'Trapezoidal'}; num2str(Ileft), num2str(Iright), num2str(Itrap)];
    best = '';
    if abs(Ileft-Itrue) < abs(Iright-Itrue) && abs(Ileft-Itrue) < abs(Itrap-Itrue)
        best = 'Left Riemann';
    elseif abs(Iright-Itrue) < abs(Ileft-Itrue) && abs(Iright-Itrue) < abs(Itrap-Itrue)
        best = 'Right Riemann';
    else
        best = 'Trapezoidal';
    end
end
```

This code first calculates the left and right Riemann sums, as well as the trapezoidal rule, using the given function `f` and the specified range and number of intervals `N`. It then calculates the true integral using the built-in `integral` function. The differences between the numerical results and the true integral are calculated, and the method with the smallest difference is chosen as the best method.

