DirectRequest.completion:
The issue you're experiencing is likely due to the fact that your bot is sending packets to the server in a synchronous manner, which can block the execution of the rest of your code. This can cause the browser to freeze or become unresponsive.

To improve this, you can use asynchronous programming techniques to send packets to the server without blocking the execution of your code. Here are a few suggestions:

1. Use `async/await` syntax to send packets:

Instead of using `ws.send()` directly, you can wrap it in an `async` function and use `await` to send the packet. This will allow your code to continue executing while the packet is being sent.

Example:
```javascript
async function sendPacket(opcode, data) {
  await ws.send(this.codec.encode(opcode, data));
}
```
2. Use `ws.send()` with a callback function:

You can pass a callback function to `ws.send()` to handle the response from the server. This will allow your code to continue executing while the packet is being sent.

Example:
```javascript
ws.send(this.codec.encode(opcode, data), (error) => {
  if (error) {
    console.error(error);
  } else {
    console.log("Packet sent successfully");
  }
});
```
3. Use a library like `ws-async`:

`ws-async` is a library that provides an asynchronous API for WebSockets. It allows you to send packets to the server without blocking the execution of your code.

Example:
```javascript
const WebSocket = require('ws-async');

//...

ws.send(this.codec.encode(opcode, data), (error, response) => {
  if (error) {
    console.error(error);
  } else {
    console.log("Packet sent successfully");
  }
});
```
4. Use a separate thread or worker:

If you're using a modern browser that supports Web Workers, you can create a separate thread or worker to handle the sending of packets to the server. This will allow your main thread to continue executing without being blocked.

Example:
```javascript
const worker = new Worker('worker.js');

worker.postMessage({ opcode: opcode, data: data });

worker.onmessage = (event) => {
  console.log("Packet sent successfully");
};
```
In your `worker.js` file, you can use the `ws` object to send the packet to the server.

Remember to always handle errors and exceptions properly when sending packets to the server.

