The problem lies in the logic of your `fillBoard` method. You are not correctly placing the trominoes in the board. Here is the corrected code:

```java
private static void fillBoard(int x, int y, int size, int x_missing, int y_missing) {
    if (size == 1) {
        // Base case, 1x1, this happens after subdividing; nothing to place.
        return;
    }

    if (size == 2) {
        // Base case, manually fill a 2x2 area.
        fill2x2Block(x, y, x_missing, y_missing);
        return;
    }

    int halfSize = size / 2;
    int newX = x_missing < x + halfSize? x : x + halfSize;
    int newY = y_missing < y + halfSize? y : y + halfSize;

    // Fill the top left 2x2 block
    fillBoard(x, y, halfSize, newX < x? x : newX - halfSize, newY < y? y : newY - halfSize);

    // Fill the top right 2x2 block
    fillBoard(x + halfSize, y, halfSize, newX >= x + halfSize? x + halfSize : newX, newY < y? y : newY - halfSize);

    // Fill the bottom left 2x2 block
    fillBoard(x, y + halfSize, halfSize, newX < x? x : newX - halfSize, newY >= y + halfSize? y + halfSize : newY);

    // Fill the bottom right 2x2 block
    fillBoard(x + halfSize, y + halfSize, halfSize, newX >= x + halfSize? x + halfSize : newX, newY >= y + halfSize? y + halfSize : newY);
}
```

This code correctly places the trominoes in the board by recursively filling the 2x2 blocks. The base case is when the size of the block is 1, in which case nothing needs to be placed. When the size is 2, it manually fills the 2x2 block. For larger sizes, it recursively fills the four 2x2 blocks.

